Smaller than the Canada Geese nearby but seem to be larger than aleutian and minima.  The head is round (instead of squarish as in aleutian and minima), bill is longer without the slight dip at the end, lack of the white neck ring (as in aleutian) and light breast contrasts sharply with the neck (unlike minima dark breast).  The white chin patch shape is also different from aleutian and minima.

Seen and photographed by many on west side channel of Oro Loma Marsh on SF Bay Trail between two bridges .    Probably a female (because it looks almost the same size as the Marbled Godwit next to it) in basic plumage.  Shorter bi-colored slightly upcurverd pink bill with dark tip, pale front without cinnamon tone and lack of obvious markings, scapulars and coverts are light grayish brown with darker center on feathers, pale grayish underwing, pale notched tertiials, barred tail and longer primary projection compared with Marbled Godwit next to it.

photos.Observation Details: Seen thru scope from between yacht club house and Skates at 9:21am for almost 4 minutes diving on and chasing after terns at the west end of the fishing pier (37.858751, -122.329356).  It's probably the same dark-morph individual that Don Simonson reported on the 18th (https://ebird.org/checklist/S73757019).  Wings are long and narrow shows very limited white on primary and underwing.  Underparts is unbarred and solid dark.  Flying pattern is 'falcon-like' with deep and fast wing beats yet still maneuver smoothly as Alex Henry described in his report (https://ebird.org/checklist/S73788784) of a different bird.  The bird eventually flying southeast towards Emeryville Marina.  A couple of super-distant shots that shows the all dark body and small head.

seen on the sand beach and boat house rooftop. Lake Merritt, Oakland California     Some key features of this gull are:  - Body size: smaller than the nearby Glaucous-winged, Western and Herring.  - Bill size: smaller/slender than Glaucous-winged and Western.  Resemble to Herring but shorter.  - Bill color: two-toned and not so clear cut as Glaucous but also not as smudged like Glaucous-winged.  - Head shape: more round (like Thayer's) instead of oval (like Glaucous-winged and Western).  - Back: pale gray mixed with pale brown.    - Tail: dark brown with thin white edges.  - Greater coverts: well-defined and contrast unlike Glaucous-winged which is smudged.  - Primaries: wingtips are brown. P5-P10 have dark outer webs where the dark on P5 and P10 and very faint.

1st-winter bird in overall warm brownish/cinnamon color tone with some new mantle feathers.  Pale head with dark eye/ear patch, heavy bill with pink base.  Structure-wise is bulky round with short primary projection.  Weak covert patterns with excessive white edges on greater coverts and tertials.  Solid dark brown tail and heavily dark spotted upper tail covert and rump.  Pale inner primary webs up to P10, which is different from HERG and VEGU, creating broader and more diffuse patch look on the wing.  Photos.
